    p.btext Oh, you cheap son of a gun! she cried in the empty hotel room, more in surprise than in anger. Then — it was the way she was built — Darlene Pullen started to laugh. She sat down in the chair beside the rumpled, abandoned bed with the quarter in one hand and the envelope it had fallen out of in the other, looking back and forth between them and laughing until tears spilled from her eyes and rolled down her cheeks. Patsy, her older kid, needed braces — Darlene had absolutely no idea how she was going to pay for them; she had been worried about it all week — and if this wasn't the final straw, what was? And if you couldn't laugh, what could you do? Find a gun and shoot yourself?

